1. WHAT IS IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference)
🔍 Definition:
IDOR happens when:
An application exposes internal object references (IDs, filenames, keys) without proper authorization checks.

💥 Example:
GET /api/user?id=1001
You change:
GET /api/user?id=1002

➡️ If you see another user’s data → IDOR confirmed

2. ACCESS CONTROL TYPES
🔄 A. HORIZONTAL PRIVILEGE ESCALATION

🔍 Meaning:
A. Same role → access other user’s data
👥 Example:
You = normal user (user1)
GET /api/orders?user_id=101
Change to:
GET /api/orders?user_id=102

➡️ You see another user’s orders → Horizontal IDOR

B. VERTICAL PRIVILEGE ESCALATION
🔍 Meaning:
Lower role → access higher role functionality
👑 Example:
Normal user accessing admin endpoint:
GET /admin/deleteUser?id=1002

➡️ If it works → Vertical escalation

3. WHERE TO FIND IDOR (REAL TARGETS)

You MUST test everywhere data is referenced by ID.

🔥 Common endpoints:
1. 🔹 User profiles
GET /api/user/123
2. 🔹 Orders / payments
GET /api/orders/567
3. 🔹 File downloads
GET /download?file=invoice_123.pdf
4. 🔹 API requests (VERY COMMON)
POST /api/update-profile
{
  "user_id": 123
}
5. 🔹 Password reset / tokens
GET /reset?user=123
6. 🔹 Hidden fields
<input type="hidden" name="user_id" value="123">
7. 🔹 Mobile APIs (GOLDMINE)
Android/iOS apps
JSON-based requests
